description.text:
I am tired of soap dishes that retain water and keep the soap rather soggy.  So I made this one that elevates the soap away from the water and has a hole that drains the water out the front into the sink.    
It works well for a first cut.  Only issue I really had was all the supports needed to make this.
No raft but supports most certainly needed.

comments.text: I really like the idea behind this, but this design would require more support material than I generally prefer to use (too much post-production sanding and such). In theory, if you make the design less modern-esque by merging the two "platters" into a more solid piece, there'd be less sharp overhangs requiring support material. Just a thought.

title: Travel mount for Taylors Gregs Wades MK6 filament feed for Ultimaker

description.text:
I have been using Taylors Ultimaker feeder for a while and i have broken the mount piece twice while travelling with my ultimaker. I will probably modify this and move the feeder another cm to the right, to line the filament intake hole over the outer area of the spool. Update 17-09-12: v2_r4
So on the second day of te maker faire i realised that the mount was sagging. Likely due to how close the stepper is to the mount.
Another 2 internal revisions, i have moved the feeder about a 1 cm closer to the right side. This helps in two ways, the mount is now not warming up as much, it also adds some more space between the large gear and the spools on the spool mount.

title: NixTech - Bumblebee 550 QuadCopter Motor/ESC Mount replacement

description.text:
For those that have the Bumblebee Quadcopter kits, this is a motor/esc mount that I redesigned to be stronger and less prone to snapping. Also added a better channel for the cables and a zip-tie groove to ensure proper mounting of the ESC.  
Using RCM 30HV ESC, and Bumblebee motors. Stock Bumblebee ESC should fit fine as well.  
Keep a lookout, i'm rebuilding the whole kit with more robust parts. Printed in PLA with no supports, Needs a litte trimming but was designed to be printed without supports.

Makerbot Replicator clone. Actually a CTC dual-extruder printer with plenty of mods from me to get accurate prints. Glass table is a plus.  
Printed in PLA with 6 shells, 60% fill. No support needed, my printer didn't have too much of a problem spanning the 27mm for the ESC. If your printer can't do that, then print with support. WIthout support there's some minor trimming around the holes. The CF arm is 14mm, this mount is a bit tight on the fit, but makes for a more stable flight. If it doesn't fit or is too tight, you can heat over stove burn to soften and then press fit the arm.  
Haven't flown it yet, still rebuilding from my last crash (inspiration for this project you can say ;P). I'll update photo's when I finish my buildout. Keep a lookout for more "NixTech" i'll be making plenty of mods to this frame.

title: Temple pieces for the board game Tikal
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This thing consists of 10 different temple pieces for the board game Tikal.  Each piece locks into the respective piece below it for stability. When your temple reaches level 10, it will be a complete Mayan temple.  
Beside the single temple layer pieces and several temple layers in one block, there are several layouts of pieces for you to choose from.  
Verdion D: Its customizable using the thingiverse customizer. When you do a customized version, all parts will be created as STL files.  
Version A (after 9 as in hexadecimal numbers): Interlocks are such that the top of each piece is flat so you can put your worker easily. It prints all upside down to make removal from the build plate easier.  
(Old) Version 7: Interlocks are a bit more loose. The bottom of each piece is tapered to get it off the printers bed easily without a raft.  
Thanks go to Harlan Martin for the write library!  
Have fun!
Printing

Print each "Upgrade_XX" and "Map_X" the number of times its needed for the board game Tikal:
3 x Upgrade_02
6 x Upgrade_03
9 x Upgrade_04
11 x Upgrade_05
8 x Upgrade_06
5 x Upgrade_07
3 x Upgrade_08
2 x Upgrade_09
1 x Upgrade_10
3 x Map_01
3 x Map_02
4 x Map_03
3 x Map_04
3 x Map_05
1 x Map_06

Alternatively if you are brave, you can use different STL files i created to print the needed parts in one go (if these fit to your build plate, its made for a Makerbot 2): Print the three STL files 'upgrades_p1', 'upgrades_p2' and 'maps_p3'. Each one fits to a makerbot2 printing area.
Together they are all the map and upgrade pieces you need for one Tikal game. You can try to print it without a raft, as the bottom of each piece is tapered to get it off the printers bed easily. If you just want to have one pyramid to see whether you like it, print the 'oneprint' file. The OpenSCAD file

Note that you need to put the Write.scad file in a subfolder called "write" to get numbers on your components when you use OpenSCAD. Beside the functions to print single temple layer pieces and several temple layers in one block, there are several layouts of pieces for you to choose from:
  • temple defines a complete temple in one block
  • tempelcut will show a complete temple with a cutout to see the inner structure
  • oneprint contains all 10 pieces needed for a single temple. Print it to test the pieces. Note that you need much more pieces to play Tikal.
  • upgrades will show the complete set of upgrade pieces needed for the game Tikal
  • maps will show the complete set of map pieces needed. Both the temples on the board and the temples on the hexagonal land pieces are taken into account. You can use these map pieces so that all temples of the same level are of the same height. During the game, whenever a hexagon with a temple is put down, select the corresponding map piece and put it into place.
  • upgrades_print1, upgrades_print2 and maps_print3 are fitting each to a makerbot2 printing area. Together they are all the map and upgrade pieces you need for one Tikal game.
    • Sorry for the use of German for variable names. Have fun!

description.text:
my own take on the classic bristlebot, with a 3D printed battery holder. Needed:
1 toothbrush
1 vibration motor
1 L1154 battery (1.5 volts)
hotglue
(googly eyes)

step 1: cut the head of a toothbrush
step 2: print the battery holder
step 3: attach the vibration motor to the battery holder and put the 2 leads into the holder block so the battery can touch it.
step 4: hotglue the holder to the toothbrush head
step 5: cut (if needed) the toothbrush hairs to length and bend them backwards so the bristlebot will go forward instead of in circles.
step 6: decorate and race!
